        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down</placeName>
                    <date>25</date>
                    <salute>My dear old Friend</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very glad you are by this time started &amp; away,<ref target="#foot.f1"/> for I fear you have been greatly overworked. Before very long I do hope you may spare time for a Sunday here.— When I read your previous note,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I swore that my fingers sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. be blistered before I gave you any more trouble; but I have eased my mind by making a list of things which I want to ask you when we meet—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> What a misfortune that your new Curator is out of health.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/> I am heartily glad that you have nevertheless started; for I always fear that you may break down.—</p>
<p>I keep on improving &amp; am now much as usual, except that anything which is hard to understand or which hurries me, knocks me up.— As soon as I have done about climbing plants I shall resume my routine work.—<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>Scott has bought his outfit, but I have not heard when he thinks of starting.—<ref target="#foot.f6"/> He has decided from cheapness for passage by the Cape; so will take your Ward’s case.—<ref target="#foot.f7"/> He is particularly obliged for your offer of directing your agent to look out for ship for him.—<ref target="#foot.f8"/> I suppose you have heard nothing more about the Coffee plantation.<ref target="#foot.f9"/> I have of course said not a word to him about it.</p>
<p>Give my kindest remembrances to M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Hooker, who I hope will profit much by your Journey—<ref target="#foot.f10"/></p>
<p>Yours affectionately | C. Darwin</p>
<p>P.S. Since writing to you I have heard from Scott &amp; he says that he shall be ready to start in about 3 weeks;<ref target="#foot.f11"/> &amp; it seems that the voyage by steam ship by the Cape is much the cheapest so this is settled unless your agent advises otherwise.</p>
<p>Now what had better be done, will you wait till your return, or will you write to your agent?</p>
<p>Perhaps the latter course will be best if you will take the trouble, but this again will depend on the coffee plantation scheme.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
